@node Program
@title "About the program"
@last Distribute
CentreQuest was written using Amiga E and assembler where needed. This is the first revision of the program released to the public and installed on my harddrive as well.

For the technically minded interested in how I pulled it off without trying to hack into the system request routines will find this information beneficial. Originally CentreQuest didn't need to replace the system requester routines. But since addition of EasyKeys, this changed s lot. Although the main code that contains the centre routine is basically the same. To do what it does, it patches OpenWindowTags().  When a program makes a call to OpenWindowTags() my code will check where it was called from and if it was from one the EasyRequest() routines then control is passed over to my centring routines that will set a new window offset. How does it do this? During the initialisation procedure it simply finds the program counter of the routine in the particular EasyRequest() code that makes the OpenWindowTags() call, then stores it for future reference. It is now used for an ID to identify an EasyRequest() function call. However to check for extra keys SysReqHandler() had to be patched. This was hard to do and 



I ended up using the original ROM code as my source and inserted my key checks in between it. If that wasn't all I found EasyRequest() to be a typical Intuition routine in that it uses internal library routines and not standard function calls. Although it might run slightly faster, it is less dynamic and I had to replace it with a routine that does exactly the same thing, only it calls system routines using a standard function call.  After all this we're just lucky that BuildEasyRequest() is left completely alone!  Mainly because this routine does all the main work and we need it intact and original. Now you know my secrets and can rest assure that you also know what my program is doing or even not doing.
@endnode

